## Conditions of Enslaved People

### Labor and Daily Life

The majority of enslaved people worked in the fields under brutal conditions. Workdays often began at dawn and ended at dusk, lasting 12 to 15 hours or more, with minimal breaks ([Softschools.com](https://www.softschools.com/language_arts/reading_comprehension/social_studies/268/slave_life_on_a_plantation/)). They cultivated labor-intensive crops such as tobacco, cotton, rice, and sugarcane. Women and men often performed similar tasks on smaller farms, while in larger plantations and Northern colonies, gendered divisions of labor were more common.

House slaves, who worked in the plantation owner’s household, sometimes experienced marginally better conditions, including better clothing and food access, but they were still subject to harsh discipline and exploitation ([PBS](https://www.pbs.org/wnet/slavery/experience/living/history.html)).

### Living Conditions

Enslaved people typically lived in crude, overcrowded cabins with dirt floors and minimal furnishings. Clothing was distributed infrequently and was often inadequate for the climate. Food rations were minimal and nutritionally poor, consisting mainly of cornmeal, fat, bacon, and vegetables, leading to malnutrition and disease ([Softschools.com](https://www.softschools.com/language_arts/reading_comprehension/social_studies/268/slave_life_on_a_plantation/); [PBS](https://www.pbs.org/wnet/slavery/experience/living/history.html)).

### Treatment and Abuse

Slaves were legally considered property and subjected to physical and sexual abuse without legal recourse. Laws prohibited slave owners from torturing slaves but allowed corporal punishment and even killing in some cases without consequences ([Slavery in the colonial history of the United States](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Slavery_in_the_colonial_history_of_the_United_States)). Female slaves were particularly vulnerable to sexual exploitation, often forced into reproductive roles to increase the slave population ([Simple English Wikipedia](https://simple.wikipedia.org/wiki/Slavery_in_the_United_States)).

---

## Economic Role of Slavery

Slavery was central to the economic development of the American colonies and later the United States, especially in the South. Plantation agriculture depended heavily on enslaved labor for profitability. The invention of the cotton gin in 1793 dramatically increased cotton production and, consequently, the demand for slave labor in the Deep South ([Foreign Policy Research Institute](https://www.fpri.org/article/2019/09/american-slavery-in-historical-perspective/)).

The internal slave trade became a significant economic activity, with hundreds of thousands of enslaved people forcibly relocated from the Upper South to the Deep South to meet labor demands ([Slavery in the colonial history of the United States](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Slavery_in_the_colonial_history_of_the_United_States)).

---

## Social and Legal Structures

### Racial Caste and Laws

Slavery in America became racialized, with laws codifying the inferior status of Africans and their descendants. The principle of *partus sequitur ventrem* ensured that slave status was inherited maternally, entrenching a racial caste system ([Slavery in the colonial history of the United States](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Slavery_in_the_colonial_history_of_the_United_States)).

Slave codes restricted the rights of enslaved people, prohibiting assembly, education, and movement. Laws also criminalized interracial marriage and restricted the rights of free people of color ([Simple English Wikipedia](https://simple.wikipedia.org/wiki/Slavery_in_the_United_States)).

### Family and Community

Slave families were often separated by sale, and paternal rights were denied to enslaved men. The social structure among slaves was often matriarchal, with mothers bearing primary responsibility for children ([Slavery in the colonial history of the United States](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Slavery_in_the_colonial_history_of_the_United_States)).

Despite oppression, enslaved people developed rich cultural and religious traditions, including the establishment of black churches and communities ([Slavery in the colonial history of the United States](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Slavery_in_the_colonial_history_of_the_United_States)).

---

## Resistance and Abolition

### Forms of Resistance

Enslaved people resisted slavery through various means, including work slowdowns, sabotage, escape, and armed rebellions such as the Stono Rebellion (1739) ([Slavery in the colonial history of the United States](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Slavery_in_the_colonial_history_of_the_United_States)).

### Abolitionist Movements

The first public American protest against slavery was a 1688 Quaker petition. Abolitionist sentiment grew during the Great Awakening and Revolutionary era, especially in Northern states, which passed gradual emancipation laws ([Slavery in the colonial history of the United States](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Slavery_in_the_colonial_history_of_the_United_States)).

### Legal End of Slavery

The international slave trade was banned in the U.S. in 1808, but domestic trade and slavery persisted. The Emancipation Proclamation of 1863 declared slaves in rebelling states free, and the Thirteenth Amendment (1865) abolished slavery nationwide ([Simple English Wikipedia](https://simple.wikipedia.org/wiki/Slavery_in_the_United_States)).

